'''Mary Jo Kilroy''' (born April 30, 1949) is an [[United States|American]] attorney and a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] politician from [[Ohio]]. Kilroy is a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative-elect]] and an outgoing two-term [[Ohio county government#Board of County Commissioners|County Commissioner]] of [[Franklin County, Ohio]], which includes the capital city of [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], including its downtown area, and some of its surrounding suburban and rural areas. Previously she served two four-year terms on the Columbus School Board after working in private practice.

In both the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2008|2008]] and [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2006|2006 United States House of Representatives elections]], Kilroy was involved in extremely close elections for [[Ohio's 15th congressional district]]. She lost in 2006 after an election that required the counting of [[absentee ballot]]s and [[election recount]]s. However, after the incumbent retired, she won a similarly close election in 2008. In both cases, she was behind after the [[Election Day (United States)|Election Day]] vote tabulations, but made up significant ground with belated absentee ballot voting results.

==Personal life==
Born in {{city-state|Euclid|Ohio}},<ref name=MJKD>{{cite web|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/2008/elections/oh/house/1170/mary-jo-kilroy/|title=Mary Jo Kilroy (D) |accessdate=2008-11-22|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> Kilroy grew up in Cleveland as the daughter of a pipefitter. Kilroy paid her way through college by working at hospitals, as a waitress and as a counselor.<ref name=MJKD/> She earned her bachelor's degree in [[political science]] from [[Cleveland State University]] in 1977 and her J.D. from [[The Ohio State University]] in 1980.<ref name=MJKD/><ref name=8taMJK/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D89661F91138&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=17 Wrangle For 4 Columbus School Board Spots|accessdate=2008-11-22|date=1991-11-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Carmen, Barbara}}</ref> Mary Jo Kilroy currently resides in the [[Clintonville]] neighborhood of [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]]. She and her husband have two college-aged daughters, Julia, a graduate student at [[Columbia University]] who attended [[Oberlin College]], and Rosa, an undergraduate at [[Brown University]]. The Kilroy's owned three dogs from animal rescue organizations at the time of the 2006 election.<ref name=8taMJK>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/060913/13kilroy.htm|title=8 things about Mary Jo Kilroy|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-09-13|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]}}</ref>

==Career==
Prior to practicing law with her husband at Handelman and Kilroy, Kilroy was a [[social worker]], hospital technician and tutor.<ref name=DE4FCSB/> In 1988, as chairman of her local branch of the National Lawyers Guild, Kilroy signed a letter urging [[List of mayors of Columbus, Ohio|Columbus Mayor]] [[Dana G. Rinehart]] to support an order in favor of creating an [[equal employment opportunity]] chief to handle race relations issues in the [[Columbus Division of Police]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11B95E3808B337F8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Mayor Urged to Block Appeal|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=1988-03-11|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Darr, Kent}}</ref> After working in private practice as a [[Partnership|partner]] in the [[law firm]] of Handelman and Kilroy with her husband,<ref name=8taMJK/> in 1991, she ran for in an eighteen-person contest for four Columbus School Board seats on a platform that included proposing to lengthen the scholastic day from six and a half hours to eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D85098D92CF0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Candidate Touts Longer School Year|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=1991-09-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Karsko, Bernie}}</ref> Kilroy was one of the four candidates to receive the endorsement of the Franklin County Democratic Party.<ref name=DE4FCSB>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D857D5CADF68&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Democrats Endorse 4 For Columbus School Board|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=1991-09-12|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Curtin, Mike}}</ref> On November 5, 1991, she placed behind incumbent board President, Sharlene Morgan, natural resources expert Robert Teater, past board member Bill Moss, which made her the fourth among the eighteen candidates and the final elected member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:Nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Mary_Jo_Kilroy&action=edit&section=2ewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D89B383213F0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=School Board President Leads Pack|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1991-11-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Stephens, Mary}}</ref>

By her second year on the seven member board, she was a unanimous selection to be second in command as Vice President of the Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E0D9344C017898&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=City Schools Considering Open Enrollment|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1993-01-05|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Beaulieu, Lovell}}</ref> She was unanimously re-elected the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E080CD2174A2E0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=School Board Members Set To Go In '94|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1994-01-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Doulin, Tim}}</ref> In her fourth year of service on the board beginning on January 3, 1995, she lost a 4<U+2013>3 election for President when the incumbent, Robert W. Teater, cast a tie-breaking vote for himself. She subsequently declined the Vice Presidency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E07CDB5C0314E0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Board Elections Reveals Signs of Division|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1995-01-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Doulin, Tim}}</ref> During her fourth year she unsuccessfully attempted to include a [[sexual orientation]] policy in the school district's nondiscrimination policy that would protect [[homosexual]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DF89C69D275930&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=First Thing The New School Board Boss Hears Is Criticism<U+2014> Views And Experience Are Questioned|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1995-01-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Doulin, Tim}}</ref> She was reelected in 1995.<ref name=MJKD/> In 1996, she contested [[Eugene Watts]] for the [[Ohio State Senate]]'s 16th district,<ref name=MJKD/> but she lost by a 51.80<U+2013>37.46% margin in a five-way contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/1990-1999OfficialElectionResults/StateSenate110596.aspx|title=State Senate: November 5, 1996|accessdate=2008-11-22|publisher=[[Ohio Secretary of State]]|work=sos.state.oh.us}}</ref> She resumed her vice presidency on January 5, 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DE419B8D66D4F8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=School Board Has Two New Leaders|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1998-01-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Doulin, Tim}}</ref> She ascended to the board's presidency for her eighth year of service to the board on January 4, 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DD3E8C230A7580&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=School Board To Pick President|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1999-01-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Alford, Roger}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DD3E8D28923EE8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Board Faces A Tough '99|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1999-01-05|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Alford, Roger}}</ref> During this eighth year, she decided not to run for re-election to a third term in order to spend more time with her family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DD3FBBAAD9A290&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Kilroy Says She Won't Run For Another Term-Columbus School Board|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=1999-08-13|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Carmen, Barbara}}</ref>

On January 6, 2000 she gained one of two Franklin County Democratic Party nominations for one of two seats to the three member Board of County Commissioners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DCF07B66198A40&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Like-Minded Democrats Unveil Endorsements For State Offices|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2000-01-07|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Cadwallader, Bruce}}</ref> The board oversees the Franklin County government's $1.3 billion budget and programs that range from child welfare to job training to minor league baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E370A8D8FE3568&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Brooks Plans To 'Get Out There' - Newcomer to board wants commissioners to raise their visibility|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2005-01-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Vitale, Robert}}</ref> On November 7, 2000, she became the first Democrat elected as a Franklin County Commissioner in eight years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DCF2BB81A48070&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Kilroy Lands Commissioner's Seat-Shoemaker easily wins re-election over Thompson|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2000-11-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Woods, Jim}}</ref> She won by a 48<U+2013>47% margin by capturing 55 of 74 [[Ward (country subdivision)|wards]] and 90% of the vote in six inner-city wards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DCF2BF1D020A68&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Inner-City Vote Drives Democratic Wins|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2000-11-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Woods, Jim}}</ref> She served as the Board's lone Democrat until she was re-elected to a second four-year term and Paula Brooks was elected on November 2, 2004 to give Democrats the majority for the first time in twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DADEF44A11AEB8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Democrats Take Reins-Kilroy, Brooks victories give party upper hand|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2004-11-03|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Vitale, Robert}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DADEF66C0A9CC8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Now In Control, Democratic Commissioners Study Options|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2004-11-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Vitale, Robert}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DADEF646E8EFA8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=County Shake-Up-Kilroy and Brooks will have the majority in January, along with the chance to bring change |accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2004-11-04|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> In her re-election she won by a 28,500 margin, which was substantially more than the 4,300 margin in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E370BC7162AB70&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Franklin County Shifts Democratic, But GOP Vows A Fight|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2005-01-16|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Vitale, Robert}}</ref> During both elections, she won despite being widely outspent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10D5491E03C604C8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=County commissioner might take on Pryce for Congress|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2005-10-18|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref> She assumed the role of Board President on January 10, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10E370AFCBDC3588&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=5 County Officials Ordered To Resign-Democratic majority says it wants leaders that share its goals|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2005-01-16|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Vitale, Robert}}</ref>

''Governing'' magazine named Franklin County as being among the five best-managed counties in the country during Kilroy's tenure. Also, Kilroy was named the Public Official of the Year by the Central Ohio Chapter of the National Association of Social Workers as a result of her role in creating the Columbus/Franklin County Affordable Housing Trust.<ref name=8taMJK/> Her term as commissioner was not without controversy, however. Kilroy came under fire during the awarding of contracts for the construction of [[Huntington Park (Columbus, Ohio)|Huntington Park]] because the lowest bid for the concrete was rejected in favor of a higher bid by a [[union shop]].<ref>{{Citation
  | last =Carmen
  | first = Barbara
  | title = Contractor sues for stadium bid
  | newspaper = The Columbus Dispatch
  | date = 2007-11-06
  | url =http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2007/11/06/Cementsuit.ART_ART_11-06-07_B1_TV8CSPI.html?type=rss&cat=&sid=101 }}</ref> Eventually the issue went to court and the commissioners decided to award the contract to the low bidder. She lost the 2006 race for U.S. Representative from {{ushr|Ohio|15|}} to Deborah Pryce, 50.2<U+2013>49.7%.<ref name=UHORN76>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2006ElectionsResults/06-1107USReps.aspx|title=U.S. House Of Representatives: November 7, 2006|accessdate=2008-10-28|year=2006|publisher=[[Ohio Secretary of State]]|work=www.sos.state.oh.us}}</ref>

==2006 Congressional Race==
:''See also [[United States House elections, 2006]]

[[Image:MaryJoVeterans.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Mary Jo Kilroy Speaking in Front of the Veterans Memorial in Columbus, Ohio.]]
Franklin County, which has elected Kilroy twice, makes up 87% of the 15th Congressional district.<ref name=O>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/campaign_diary/ohio/archive/2006/06/overview.htm|title=Overview|accessdate=2008-10-29|date=2006-06-17|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]}}</ref> The 2006 race in Ohio's 15th district gained significant national attention as it was seen as one of a handful of seats that Democrats had an opportunity to gain from Republicans. As of mid-October, the race was generally considered to be a toss-up largely due to incumbent Representative Pryce's leadership in the [[United States Republican Party|GOP]].<ref name="Giroux">{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/cq/2006/10/13/cq_1625.html|title=Pryce's Role in GOP Leadership Contribures to Race's Tossup Status|accessdate=2008-10-28|date=2006-10-13|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|work=[[New York Times]]|author=Giroux, Greg}}</ref><ref name = "Tumulty">{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1546415,00.html|title=CampaCampaign '06: No Politics Is Local in Ohio"|accessdate=2008-10-28|date=2006-10-16|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Karen Tumulty}}</ref> Pryce had not had a close contest since her first election in 1992 and had garnered 10% more of the vote than [[George W. Bush]] in 2004.<ref name = "Tumulty"/> However, Pryce was vulnerable due to Ohio Republican Party ([[Bob Taft]] and [[Bob Ney]]) scandals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1539428,00.html|title=Campaign 2006: The Battle for Ohio, Round Two|accessdate=2008-10-29|date=2006-09-26|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Bacon, Perry, Jr.}}</ref> the lagging Ohio economy,<ref name=TTPR/> her association with controversial [[Dennis Hastert]] and [[Mark Foley]],<ref name = "Tumulty"/><ref name=TTPR/><ref name=EG>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1552047,00.html|title=Election Guide|accessdate=2008-10-29|date=2006-10-29|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref name=AHRfODP>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/blogs/erbe/2006/10/23/a-horse-race-for-ohios-deborah-pryce.html|title=A Horse Race for Ohio's Deborah Pryce|accessdate=2008-11-08|date=2006-10-23|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]}}</ref> and backlash to Republican support of the [[Iraq War]].<ref name = "Tumulty"/><ref name=TTPR/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time-blog.com/real_clear_politics/2006/09/the_sour_mood_in_columbus.html|title=The Sour Mood in Columbus|accessdate=2008-10-29|date=2006-09-11|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Real Clear Politics]]|author=Bevan, Tom}}</ref> Another Ohio Republican scandal in the minds of Ohio voters during the 2006 campaign was [[Coingate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.nytimes.com/external/comments/elections.nytimes.com/2008/results/states/ohio.html?|title=Reader's Comments: Ohio|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2008-11-05|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Springfield, Johnny}}</ref> Pryce and the Republicans had to keep conservative independent, Charles Morrison, off the ballot to have their best shot at success.<ref name=O/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/campaign_diary/ohio/archive/2006/06/overview.htm|title=Campaign Diary: Ohio|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-06-17|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]}}</ref> A month before the election, Pryce was 12&nbsp;points behind Kilroy.<ref name=AHRfODP/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/campaign_diary/ohio_fifteen/archive/2006/11/republican_pryce_stays_on_offe_1.htm#more|title=Republican Pryce Stays on Offense in Defense of Seat|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-11-06|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Brush, Silla}}</ref> On the eve of the election, some experts, such as ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', considered Pryce the underdog.<ref name=TTPR>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1555510,00.html|title=The Tipping Point Races: Pryce v. Kilroy|accessdate=2008-10-29|date=2006-11-06|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> Kilroy was expected to be the beneficiary of the decade-long migration of conservative voters to suburbs outside of the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/060619/19ohio_4.htm|title=Hot Spot: All the issues that are key to this fall's elections are on display in Ohio|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-06-11|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Gilgoff, Dan}}</ref>

After regular ballots were counted, Pryce led Kilroy by over 3,500 votes with about 19,000 provisional ballots outstanding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/bulletin/bulletin_061124.htm|title=Campaign News: 2006 Elections Still Not Finished|accessdate=2008-11-08|date=2006-11-24|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/061108/8diary_6.htm|title=In the End, Pivotal Races Tipped to Democrats|accessdate=2008-11-08|date=2006-11-08|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Halloran, Liz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/11/us/politics/11ohio.html?|title=Ohio Election Win Challenged|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-11-11|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hamill, Sean D.}}</ref> The Franklin county absentee and provisional ballots were not counted until approximately two weeks after the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/cq/2006/11/09/cq_1929.html?|title=Senate is Set, But Final House Results May Take Weeks|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-11-09|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Kapochunas, Rachel, Greg Giroux, Lauren Phillips, Marc Rehmann and David Miller }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/18/sports/ncaafootball/18buckeyes.html?|title=For Top 2, Grief Adds to Lore of the Big Game|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-11-18|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Thamel, Pete}}</ref> On Monday November 27, nearly three weeks after Election Day, Pryce was declared the winner by a 1,054 vote margin that mandated a recount.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/28/us/politics/28ohio.html?|title=Republican Named Winner in Ohio House Race, but Recount Looms|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-11-28|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Driehaus, Bob}}</ref> After two recounts and all of the votes were counted, Congresswoman Deborah Pryce (R) prevailed over Democratic challenger Mary Jo Kilroy. The Franklin County Board of Elections announced the results Monday morning December 11, 2006. Pryce (R) gained 25 votes and Kilroy (D) gained 18 votes in the recount of votes in Franklin, Union, and Madison Counties in Ohio. Pryce won with 50.20% of the vote by a 110,739<U+2013>109,677 margin.<ref name=UHORN76/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/12/us/politics/12brfs-CONGRESS.html?|title=Ohio: Pryce Declared Winner in Congressional Race|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-12-12|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Kilroy felt her campaign was slowed by the early candidacy of fellow Franklin County Commissioner Paula Brooks, who eventually withdrew, and immediately after losing in 2006, she announced she would recontest the seat in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0707/5078_Page2.html|title=Lazarus candidacies unlikely to lure voters|accessdate=2008-10-28|date=2007-07-23|publisher=Capitol News Company, LLC |work=[[The Politico]]|author=Kraushaar, Josh}}</ref>

Kilroy made an issue of Pryce's knowledge of the Foley scandal and the need for Hastert to resign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/061008/16congress_2.htm|title=The fury of the Foley scandal is threatening to sink Republican candidates in races across the country|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-10-08|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Gilgoff, Dan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/061004/4foleyraces.htm|title=Foley Scandal Resonates in Close Congressional Campaigns|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-10-04|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Brush, Silla}}</ref> Kilroy also linked her opponent to the unpopular Republican administration and congressional majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/03/politics/03ohio.html?|title=Democrats Sense Chances in Ohio for 2006 Vote|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2005-12-03|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Stolberg, Sheryl Gay}}</ref> After Foley resigned following the [[Page (servant)|page]] scandal, Kilroy attacked price with the conservative religious voters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/12/us/politics/12cong.html?|title=Foley Case Snags House Incumbent in Ohio|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2006-10-12|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Nagourney, Adam}}</ref> Kilroy ran [[radio commercial]]s on Christian and conservative [[radio station]]s in an attempt to appeal to family-values-oriented listeners.<ref name=AHRfODP/>

Two debates were held for this race during the 2006 election cycle. The first took place September 18,<ref name = "debate1">{{cite web|author=Nash, James|url=http://www.columbusdispatch.com/?story=dispatch/2006/09/19/20060919-D1-04.html|title=Pryce, Kilroy trade jabs on Iraq, Bush, tax cuts|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|date=2006-09-19|acessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref> and the second was on October 12.<ref name = "onn">{{cite web|work=[[Ohio News Network]]|url=http://www.onnnews.com/?sec=home&story=sites/10tv/content/pool/200610/1469857270.html|title=Kilroy, Pryce Square Off in Debate"|date=2006-10-13|accessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref><ref name = "Rowland">{{cite web|author=Rowland, Darrel|url=http://www.columbusdispatch.com/election/election.php?story=219033|title=Sparks fly as Kilroy, Pryce spar|work=[[Columbus Dispatch]]|date=2006-10-13|accessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref> In the first debate Kilroy and incumbent U.S. Representative, Pryce discussed the war in Iraq, the War on Terror, taxes, social security, the federal deficit and President Bush. In the final week before the election, Pryce attempted to demand another debate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A05EEDB133FF931A35752C1A9609C8B63|title=THE 2006 CAMPAIGN; Concentration of Competitive Races Puts Ohio at Center of Midterm Battle|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2005-11-02|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Kirkpatrick, David D.}}</ref>

The second debate was marked by a more heated exchange on behalf of both participants. Kilroy referred to Pryce as a "right-wing apologist" and said that "Deborah Pryce continues to distort my record."<ref name = "Rowland"/> Meanwhile Pryce described her opponent as a "far left fringe Democrat" and said that Kilroy "spews lies and misinformation."<ref name = "Rowland"/> The debate was attended by 400 people at the [[Ohio State University]] Fawcett Center and reporters from as far away as Ireland.

==2008 Congressional Race==
{{seealso|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2008}}
