</div>In August 2007, incumbent Pryce announced her retirement at the end of her elected term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time-blog.com/real_clear_politics/2007/08/08_notes_bye_bye_buckeye.html|title='08 Notes: Bye Bye Buckeye|accessdate=2008-12-21|date=2007-08-16|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/blogs/news-desk/2007/08/16/house-gop-retirements-grow.html|title=House GOP Retirements Grow|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2007-08-16|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Brush, Silla}}</ref> The Democrats felt that the seat continued to be vulnerable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/070411/11housedems.htm|title=Democrats Optimistic on Midwest House Seats|accessdate=2008-10-29|date=2007-04-11|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Brush, Silla}}</ref> Kilroy announced her intention to again seek the 15th District seat in 2008. She ran against Republican [[Steve Stivers]], a State Senator from the 16th District, [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] [[Mark M. Noble]], and Independent candidate Don Elijah Eckhart.<ref name=RtW0/> The race was considered to be one of the most important United State House of Representative races to watch in the country.<ref name=RtW0>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1849130_1849126_1852166,00.html|title=Races to Watch '08: Why an Uncharismatic Liberal May Win in Moderate Ohio|accessdate=2008-10-27|date=2008-10-20|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Maag, Christopher}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1815495_1815420_1815414,00.html|title=Top 15 House and Senate Races to Watch: Ohio, 15th District|accessdate=2008-10-27|date=2008-06-17|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Downie, James and Marti Covington}}</ref> The last Democrat to hold the 15th district was [[Robert T. Secrest]] in the mid 1960s, but with Republican voters moving out of the district into the northern suburbs of {{city-state|Columbus|Ohio}} since the 1990s, the district became more evenly matched.<ref name=RtW0/>

In April 2008, the Sierra Club again endorsed Kilroy's candidacy.<ref name = "Sierra Club Endorsement">{{cite web|url=http://blog.dispatch.com/dailybriefing/2008/04/sierra_club_endorses_kilroy.shtml|title=Sierra Club endorses Kilroy|work=[[Columbus Dispatch]]|date=2008-04-28|accessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref>

Stivers led Kilroy by a 129,852<U+2013>129,703 margin with 100% of the Election Day precincts counted, but before the provisional ballots were counted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/results/individual/#mapHOH/H/15|title=U.S. House: Ohio 15|accessdate=2008-11-09|date=2008-11-07|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1244CB9C783EBA38&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Kilroy, Stivers may be in for long wait in 15th|accessdate=2008-11-10|date=2008-11-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|author=Nash, James and Jim Siegel}}</ref> On November 25, 2008 [[Madison County, Ohio|Madison]] and [[Union County, Ohio|Union Counties]] concluded their absentee, military, and provisional ballot counting and Stivers claimed a net gain resulting in a 594 vote lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politickeroh.com/daviddewitt/stivers-camp-touts-madison-county-results-kilroy-camp-says-it-s-happy-too|title=Stivers camp touts Madison County results, Kilroy camp says it<U+2019>s happy too|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2008-11-25|work=PolitickerOH.com|author=Dewitt, David}}</ref> On December 5, 2008, Stivers' supporters won a ruling in the Ohio Supreme Court that the 1,000 provisional ballots that lacked signatures or had names and signatures in the wrong places be thrown out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politickeroh.com/justinmiller/stivers-supporters-win-supreme-court-case|title=Stivers supporters win Supreme Court case|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2008-12-05|work=PolitickerOH.com|author=Miller Justin}}</ref> On December 7, 2008, Franklin County Election Canvassers completed their final ballot count, which included absentee, military, and provisional ballots received within ten days of Election Day, giving Kilroy a victory margin of 2,311 votes over Stivers. This margin exceeds the automatic recount margin of 0.5%. Stivers conceded the race to Kilroy later on Sunday.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2008/12/07/election.html |title=Kilroy is headed to Congress: Democrat defeats Stivers in 15th Congressional District |publisher=[[Columbus Dispatch]] |date=2008-12-07 |accessdate=2008-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politickeroh.com/justinmiller/stivers-leads-kilroy-390-votes |title=Stivers leads Kilroy by 390 votes &#124; PolitickerOH |publisher=Politickeroh.com |author=JUSTIN MILLER |date= |accessdate=2008-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1108/15351.html |title=Eight races still too close to call-Andy Barr-Politico.com |publisher=Politico.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Majors, Stephen|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iThPAYm76gLicdTq9np-hwoFqaJgD94U67KO0|title=Democrat wins central Ohio congressional race|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2008-12-07}}</ref>

Kilroy will be the first Democrat to represent the district in 42 years (since Secrest).<ref name=RtW0/> She will be only the second Democrat to represent a significant portion of Columbus since 1967. The last Democrat to represent the city, [[Bob Shamansky]] represented the neighboring 12th District from 1981 to 1983.

The late ballots were of three types:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uaprogressiveaction.com/taxonomy/term/28|title=GOTV continues in the 15th district and we need your help to elect Mary Jo Kilroy!!!!!|accessdate=2008-12-08|date=2008-11-07|publisher=Upper Arlington Progressive Action }}</ref>
# the military and overseas absentee ballots postmarked by the time the polls closed Tuesday November 4 and received by November 14;
# any domestic absentee ballots postmarked by Monday November 3 that are received by November 14;
# as well as any of the estimated 5,000 absentee ballots with errors that voters correct by November 14.

